I've been playing off and on with using pint with matplotlib--version 1.5 of matplotlib has some crucial fixes for using pint with the units support. Here's the code I've used to enable the registration, but I haven't played around enough to know if it's sufficient:
```python
import matplotlib.units as munits

# Implementation of matplotlib support for unit conversion using pint
class PintConverter(munits.ConversionInterface):
    @staticmethod
    def convert(value, unit, axis):
        return value.to(unit)

    @staticmethod
    def axisinfo(unit, axis):
        return None

    @staticmethod
    def default_units(x, axis):
        return x.to_base_units()


# Register the class
munits.registry[units.Quantity] = PintConverter()
```

This is the reason:

> ‘std::vector >::size_type {aka unsigned int}’

And it means that sizeof(unsigned long) > sizeof(size_t)

Fast and ugly solution can help to build this sample without changing library itself:
add this function before including dlib/dnn.h

```
namespace std{
    inline const unsigned long
    min(const unsigned long& __a, const size_t& __b)
    {
        if (__b < __a)
            return (const unsigned long)__b;
        return __a;
    }
}
```

Looks like trainer code should be changed to exclude this in a future

Other parts of library should work well. If you do not need DNN samples on rasberry Pi, you can build them expicitly:

`cmake --build . --target face_detection_ex`

If you have 2 vectors A and B, declared as a matrix<double> for example, then you can just do this:
hash_similar_angles_256 h;
auto hash1 = h(A);
auto hash2 = h(B);
cout << "hamming distance: " << h.distance(hash1,hash2) << endl;

@maroux I like the `Serializer(instance=obj).data` and `Serializer(data=data).instance`

I think it would be more flexible to have a function instead of just specifying the class for deserialization in case some extra massaging of the data has to be done before returning the instance. So if we had a `make_instance` function that takes the serialized data you could make the .instance property something like:
```py
def make_instance(self, data):
  return SomeClass(**data)

@property
def instance(self):
  if self._instance is None:
    self._instance = self.make_instance(self.to_internal_value(self._data))
  return self._instance
```
by default make_instance could just be a noop

