Just ran into this as well while testing.

The chain of events are:

view calls LoginForm.validate(), executing this code:

    def validate(self):
        if not super(LoginForm, self).validate():
            return False

        if self.email.data.strip() == '':
            self.email.errors.append(get_message('EMAIL_NOT_PROVIDED')[0])
            return False

        if self.password.data.strip() == '':
            self.password.errors.append(get_message('PASSWORD_NOT_PROVIDED')[0])
            return False

        self.user = _datastore.get_user(self.email.data)
        ## more validation follows.

`get_user()` is polymorphic depending on the database backend used. In peewee it looks like this:

    def get_user(self, identifier):
        try:
            return self.user_model.get(self.user_model.id == identifier)
        except ValueError:
            pass

        for attr in get_identity_attributes():
            column = getattr(self.user_model, attr)
            try:
                return self.user_model.get(column ** identifier)
            except self.user_model.DoesNotExist:
                pass

So the datastore will always try to search by id first if you give it something that looks like a number.

A workaround, as you have found, is to put some validation on the form field. This is supported in the framework by subclassing the form. From the documentation -

[Customizing Views](https://pythonhosted.org/Flask-Security/customizing.html#forms)

Should flask-security should be smarter about this or leave it up to the user to deal with?

@sander76 my take on this is to use exceptions. You know what return codes are valid for each of the methods, everything else should raise an exception. 

For example in `put`, you just log an error and return None for `ValueError`, `TimeoutError` and `ClientError`  but what if the user needs to distinguish between a timeout and a wrong request? There is no way to do that now but to parse logs.

The users of these methods (i.e. `Shade`, `Scene` etc) should catch this exceptions if needed and recover, otherwise the exceptions should propagate higher up (i.e. `PowerView` platform in HA)

I didn't realize that the `p` tag could also be used in the if. Adding this seems to have solved my issue. Thanks for the help everyone!

For reference, here's what changed:
```
This is a test.
{%p for thing in things %}
{%p if thing.name == "foo" %}
{{ thing.name }}
{%p endif %}
{%p endfor %}
More **things**
