The thread needs to voluntarily exit. From the outside you can send a signal to tell the thread to exit, and that would be a condition in the loop. For example, you can do it with an Event object:

    exit_event = Event()

    def thread():
        while not exit_event.is_set():
            # do some work here

So then when you want the thread to end, just call `exit_event.set()` from any other thread, and then wait for the thread to end on its own, maybe with a `thread.join()` call.

I'm not ignoring this, I've just been thinking about this feature and while it does have some interesting ideas I'm still not sure about it.

First of all, it seems most of what this extension does can be easily implemented by the application inside a class-based namespace. Something like this:

    class ClassBasedInterceptor(Namespace):
        def ignore_for(self, event, *args):
            return False

        def before_event(self, event, *args):
            return args

        def after_event(self, event, ret):
            return ret

        def exception_handler(self, exc):
            raise exc

        def trigger_event(self, event, *args):
            try:
                if not self.ignore_for(event, *args):
                    new_args = self.before_event(event, *args)
                    ret = super(MyNamespace, self).trigger_event(event, *new_args)
                    return self.after_event(event, ret)
            except Exception as exc:
                return self.exception_handler(exc)

Isn't the above namespace almost equivalent to the functionality of your patch?

I think the only thing this does not have is the chaining of multiple interceptors. That is actually one of the problems I have with this feature. WSGI middlewares are very friendly to chaining because they can run pretty much in any order. Each middleware takes two arguments, and it passes them on to the next middleware, either modified or not, but there are always the same two arguments. Your interceptor design can modify the list of arguments, and this makes the order in which interceptors run very important. If the interceptor somehow get added in the wrong order, then things are not going to work.

