Problem fixed, however this could be a potential bug in the code.
within "openthread/examples/posix/platform/radio.c" line 258-266 

`static inline void getExtAddress(const uint8_t *frame, otExtAddress *address) 
{
    size_t i;

    for (i = 0; i < sizeof(address); i++) {
        address->m8[i] = frame[IEEE802154_DSTADDR_OFFSET + (7 - i)];
    }
}`

as "address" is a pointer doing "sizeof" will return the number of Bytes used in the pointer, not the size of the address itself. When dealing with 64 bit pointers and addresses it workes out fine as both are the same, however, the Pi uses 32 bit pointers, so it was calculating the address length to be 32 bits, meaning that half of the address length is missing during processing.

the code should read  
`static inline void getExtAddress(const uint8_t *frame, otExtAddress *address)
{
    size_t i;

    for (i = 0; i < sizeof(s_extended_address); i++)
    {
        address->m8[i] = frame[IEEE802154_DSTADDR_OFFSET + (sizeof(s_extended_address) - 1 - i)];
    }
}`

I don't mind capability, but it needs to be implemented in a way that preserves the string in the memory of the image. We do firmware upgrade checks by fetching the firmware version string from the NCP and then searching for that exact string somewhere in the firmware image that we are considering installing. If the string is found, we assume no firmware upgrade is necessary. If the string is not found, we assume that we have a different firmware image and go ahead and install it.

One way to fix this is to not use `printf`-style construction, but use the preprocessor macros directly. We can do that by moving the construction of that version check string into OpenThread and making it the `otGetPlatformVersion()` command:

```
const char *otGetPlatformVersion(void)
{
    static const char sPlatformVersion[] = PACKAGE_NAME "/" PACKAGE_VERSION "; " OPENTHREAD_EXAMPLES "; " __DATE__ " " __TIME__;

    return sPlatformVersion;
}
```

...and then we can have both the CLI and NCP directly return that string.

On an unrelated note, we should really rename `OPENTHREAD_EXAMPLES`. It is very confusing how it is being used in this context.

